[reasoning process] To find the radical conjugate of the expression \( 2\sqrt{7} - 1 \), we need to understand what a radical conjugate is. The radical conjugate of an expression of the form \( a + b\sqrt{c} \) is given by \( a - b\sqrt{c} \). In this case, we can identify \( a = -1 \), \( b = 2 \), and \( c = 7 \). Therefore, to find the radical conjugate, we switch the sign of the term involving the square root: 

\[
\text{Radical Conjugate} = -1 - 2\sqrt{7}
\]

[Verification] We can confirm our work by recalling that the radical conjugate operates only on the square root part of the expression while keeping the non-radical part the same. Here, the term with the square root, \( 2\sqrt{7} \), is negated to produce \( -2\sqrt{7} \) while the constant part, which is \( -1 \), remains unchanged. Thus, this matches with our computed radical conjugate.

[Final Answer] The answer is \\boxed{-1 - 2\sqrt{7}} \n#### -1 - 2\sqrt{7}

